ns, and dynamic descriptor support. Includes thread-safe token management with mutex protection.\n\n- **HTTP Local Rate Limit Filter** (`source/extensions/filters/http/local_ratelimit/local_ratelimit.h` and `.cc`): Integrates local rate limiting into HTTP filter chain with per-route and per-connection rate limiters.\n\n- **Network Local Rate Limit Filter** (`source/extensions/filters/network/local_ratelimit/`): Provides local rate limiting at the connection level.\n\n### Kubernetes Rate Limiting Implementation\n\nKubernetes implements rate limiting at the API server level with two complementary mechanisms:\n\n#### 1. API Server Rate Limiting (Token Bucket)\n\nBasic token bucket rate limiter for client-side API access:\n\n- **Token Bucket Rate Limiter** (`staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/util/flowcontrol/throttle.go`): Implements `RateLimiter` interface with `tokenBucketRateLimiter` struct. The `NewTokenBucketRateLimiter()` function creates a rate limiter with configurable QPS and burst capacity using Go's `golang.org/x/time/rate` package.\n\n- **Passive Rate Limiter Interface**: Provides non-blocking `TryAccept()` method for immediate token availability checks without blocking.\n\n#### 2. API Priority and Fairness (APF) - Priority Level Handling\n\nAdvanced flow control mechanism for managing request prioritization at the API server level:\n\n- **APF Filter** (`staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/util/flowcontrol/apf_filter.go`): Core interface `Interface` defines the `Handle()` method that orchestrates request queuing and dispatching based on flow schema classification and priority level configuration. It supports work estimation and execution notification.\n\n- **APF Controller** (`staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/util/flowcontrol/apf_controller.go`): Manages configuration digestion of FlowSchema and PriorityLevelConfiguration API objects. Implements borrowing between priority levels with periodic seat adjustment. The `StartFunction` initiates request handling by determining priority level and queuing decisions based on descriptors.\n\n- **Context** (`staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/util/flowcontrol/apf_context.go`): Provides context information for in-flight requests.\n\n- **Fair Queuing Queue Set** (`staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/util/flowcontrol/fairqueuing/queueset/queueset.go`): Implements Fair Queuing for Server Requests (FQSR) algorithm with:\n  - Priority level specific queue sets\n  - FIFO list management (`fifo_list.go`)\n  - Event clock interface for deterministic testing\n  - Concurrent request tracking with seat management\n  - Request dispatch guarantees for fairness\n\n- **Concurrency Allocation** (`staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/util/flowcontrol/conc_alloc.go`): Manages seat allocation and concurrency limits per priority level with support for borrowing from lower priority levels.\n\n- **Max Seats Tracking** (`staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/util/flowcontrol/max_seats.go`): Tracks maximum seats (concurrency units) allocatable per priority level based on work estimation.\n\n### Pattern Comparison\n\n**Envoy** implements a flexible, service-level rate limiting pattern with both centralized (global) and local approaches, allowing proxies to make independent rate limiting decisions or defer to a centralized service.\n\n**Kubernetes** implements a sophisticated server-side rate limiting pattern focused on fairness and prioritization, where the API server manages request queuing based on user-defined FlowSchemas and PriorityLevelConfigurations with built-in support for seat borrowing between priority levels.\n\nBoth systems use token bucket as the underlying rate limiting algorithm but differ in scope (network proxy vs API server) and complexity (simple global/local vs sophisticated fairness-aware APF)."
